thoughts.a: Input and output grids are the same sizes. Input grid contains horizontal and vertical black lines that split the input grid into a 3x3 supergrid. Each subsection of this supergrid is made up of a 5x5 green color background tiles. Each subsection also has some number of red tiles in that 5x5 tile square. These shapes are likely to be meaningful to the transformation rule. The output grid looks remarkably similar to the input grid, with the exception that the subsections of green color background and red tiles have been rearranged within the 3x3 supergrid. How do we know where to place each subsection in the output grid? The shape of the red tiles within each subsection determines where that subsection should be located. Basically the output grid's 3x3 supergrid is an organized, or shape sorted, version of the of the input grid. The relative location of the red tiles inside each subsection determines the relative location of that subsection in the output grid. For example, the subsection that goes in the top left of the output grid's supergrid has red tiles going in a diagonal direction in the top left of the 5x5 tile subsection. The subsection that goes in the middle row, right column of the 3x3 supergrid has red tiles that are located only roughly in the middle row, right columns of the 5x5 green tile subsection. This trend continues for all the subsections, including the center subsection, which has a more centered-flavored red tile pattern that is symmetric in the horiztonal and vertical directions. Thus the hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain a supergrid of 3x3 subsections, denoted by some color of vertical and horizontal lines. Each subsection will have a common background color, and some color of shapes that will help us to determine the output grid. In order to construct the output grid, we need to move each subsection, regardless of where they start in the input grid, into their appropriate locations. Their appropriate locations are dictated by the shape of the internal red tiles, as described above. The relative locations of the subsections will be similar to the relative locations of the red tiles in the subsections.
